Reflections on the very American ideal of labour rights as human rights
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have introduced a bill to establish the organization of trade unions as a civil right.
“As unions die, so do middle-class jobs,” said Ellison, a Minnesota Democrat and deputy chairman of the Progressive Caucus in Congress.
That is why I proudly present the Employee Entitlement Act together with the civil rights icon John Lewis.
This groundbreaking law gives workers the same legal opportunities for discrimination on the grounds of trade union organization as it does for other forms of discrimination – and thus stops anti-union forces.
Complementing the national labour law to create an opportunity for discriminatory workers to organize a trade union representation, to sue before a civil court for justice - and to receive compensation or penalties - is a sensible and necessary initiative.
But it is certainly not a radical initiative - at least not according to American standards.
In fact, the best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and the other sponsors of their bill propose is to link back to a very American idea.
Despite the setbacks to which unions have been exposed in recent years – in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states across the country – Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to recognize, expand and uphold labor rights.
There was a time that millions of Americans still remember when this country called democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press and the right to unite in one breath.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas Mac Arthur and his staff encouraged the country to pass a constitution designed to ensure that the militarized autocracy of Hedki Tojos would be replaced by democracy.
Fully aware that the workers and their unions had a role to play in the creation of a new Japan, they used a language that explicitly recognized that "the rights of workers to union and joint negotiation and action are guaranteed."
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his staff urged the Germans to write a constitution that would ensure that fascism would replace Adolf Hitler with a strong democracy.
In recognition of the fact that the workers would have to organise themselves, and should raise their voices in the new nation, the Germans inserted a clause that explicitly stated: "The right to form associations to secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and every guaranteed profession or profession.
Agreements that restrict or restrict this right are null and void; measures aimed at it are unlawful.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights as adopted by the United Nations as a global agreement in 1948, Roosevelt and the other authors included a guarantee that "everyone has the right to join or form trade unions to protect them."
For generations, Americans have accepted the basic premise that labor rights are human rights.
As this country advises other countries on how to shape civil and democratic societies, Americans explained that the right to form a union – and to have that union participate in collective bargaining as equal partners with companies and government agencies – must be protected.
After these rights have been under fire in America, it is indeed very wise to reconsider the American ideal, according to which the working population must have the right to unite and be heard in a free and open society.
As Pastor Martin Luther King Jr. said fifty years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Now everyone knows that the workers’ movement did not limit the strength of the nation, but rather enlarged it.
By raising the standard of living of millions of people, work miraculously created a market for industry and elevated the entire nation to unimaginable levels of production.
Those who attack the work forget these simple truths, but history preserves them.
History remembers, and so should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of the protection of civil rights as protection against discrimination in the creation of workers' representations - is long overdue.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis renew the ideals that made America great in the past and redeemed the promise of democracy.
Judge Temporarily Stops Law That Could Force All Abortion Clinics in Louisiana to Close
A U.S. federal judge on Sunday temporarily halted the implementation of a law in Louisiana that lawyers say would likely have led to the closure of all five state abortion clinics.
