However, the judge’s decision means that doctors can continue to legally perform abortions temporarily while applying for such a right.
"The plaintiffs can continue to work in accordance with the law while striving to obtain these rights," Federal Judge John deGravelles wrote in his judgment.
Within one month, a hearing will be set up for the judge to bring about a more lasting decision for the law.
Abortion advocates welcomed the decision, the latest in a series of judgments against similar measures, saying doctors were thus gaining more time to obtain hospital admission rights.
“Today’s decision means that women in Louisiana are evading a fraudulent law that wants to take away their health and their rights,” said Nancy Northup, president and president of the Center for Reproductive Rights, which had sued on behalf of three of the state’s five clinics to stop the law.
It was not immediately clear whether the verdict also extended to the doctors from the two clinics who did not join the suit and also applied for inclusion rights.
Louisiana is one of 11 states that have enacted similar laws, with courts recently declaring such measures unconstitutional in Alabama and Mississippi.
Key areas of a Texas law that would have forced most of the state's remaining clinics to close were halted by a federal judge on Friday.
Abortion advocates and the American College of Ostertricians and Gynecologists, as well as the American Medical Association, agree that admission rights require unnecessary restrictions from doctors.
Opponents of abortion oppose the idea that the measures are designed to protect women’s health, although some also welcomed the impact of the closure of clinics.
Only one doctor who performs abortions in Louisiana has patient access rights, the Center for Reproductive Rights said.
If all other doctors in the state are forced to stop performing abortions, this doctor would no longer perform the operation for his safety, the group said.
In their argument against the verdict, representatives of the state of Louisiana said they would not punish doctors for carrying out abortions while their applications for patient enrollment rights were still pending.
