If you would like to take photos or videos underwater, there is a choice of devices.
The cheapest option is a waterproof point-and-shoot, such as the Nikon Coolpix AW120 or an action cam such as the GoPro Hero3+ Silver Edition, both of which are available for around $300.
I took these photos at a family party with multiple cameras, all of which are available at a price of under $350.
Regardless of the equipment, there are a few rules for the best results.
Inspect your equipment twice.
Even if you have a waterproof camera, make sure the battery compartment and other compartments are sealed tight.
Also, set your camera to the photos or videos you want to capture.
Some cameras and camcorders feature scene and recording modes that optimize exposure time for dazzling underwater conditions.
And before you jump in, check to what depth your equipment is working.
Some cameras are only allowed for up to 5 feet, others up to 50 or 60 feet.
Search our shopping guide and the ratings for digital cameras for conventional and waterproof models.
Take multiple shots - because many won't fold.
Point-and-shoot cameras have an LCD that allows you to compose images, Action Cams usually don’t.
Even if you have an LCD, it’s hard to see this underwater, and the right image setting is a lucky thing.
So make a lot of footage.
If your camera has a row mode that takes a series of shots with slightly changed exposure settings, use it.
Stay close to the surface.
The light gets dramatically worse as you move away from the surface.
So if possible, stay close to the surface when taking pictures in a pool, a lake or the sea.
This also allows you to add more color to your photos; the deeper you go, the less color you will see.
Get close to the objects.
This is also a good advice on land, but it is all the more important underwater because of the poor lighting conditions.
This is especially important when working with an action cam: These devices often have a fixed wide-angle lens, which means you need to get closer to your objects when they are meant to fill the entire frame.
