Norwegian Cruise just ahead of a $3 billion deal with Prestige Cruises
Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings Ltd NCHL.O, the world’s third-largest cruise operator, is conducting advanced negotiations to acquire competitor Prestige Cruises International Inc for approximately $3 billion, according to industry experts.
A deal would give Norwegian Cruises, a company with a market value of $6.8 billion, access to Prestige Cruises’ luxury cruise ships as well as its wealthy customers, while competing with larger rivals such as Royal Caribbean Cruises Ltd (RCL.N) and Carnival Corp (CCL.N).
An agreement could be announced as early as this week, the sources said on Sunday, warning that the talks could also end in vain.
The owner of Prestige Cruises, the private equity company Apollo Global Management LLC (APO.N) also owns a 20 percent stake in Norwegian Cruises.
The sources asked to remain anonymous as the negotiations were not public.
Representatives of Norwegian Cruise and Prestige Cruises did not respond to requests for comments, while a spokesman for Apollo declined a comment.
The Miami-based company Norwegian Cruise operates 13 cruise ships on routes between North America, the Mediterranean, the Baltic, Central America and the Caribbean.
Its revenues were $2.57 billion in 2013, an increase of 13 percent compared to 2012.
Prestige Cruises, also based in Miami, operates under the brand names Oceania and Regent, which together operate eight cruise ships on routes to Scandinavia, Russia, the Mediterranean, North America, Asia, Africa and South America.
It reported revenues for 2013 of $1.2 billion, an increase of 6% compared to the previous year.
The cruise industry stands at a total of around $29 billion and is expected to grow in the next few years due to the strengthening of the middle class in emerging countries such as China and India.
The companies are trying to position themselves as the best choice for these new customers among the cruise providers.
Prestige Cruises applied to the U.S. regulators in January 2014.
Apollo has been the majority shareholder in the company since a $850 million deal in 2007.
Norwegian Cruises was formed in its current form in 2000 through a merger with a cruise carrier owned by Genting Bhd (GENT.KL), a leisure and casino company controlled by Malaysian billionaire Lim Kok Thay.
Apollo invested $1 billion in Norwegian Cruise in 2008.
Norwegian Cruise entered the stock market in January 2013.
At the end of June, Genting held 28 percent of the shares, Apollo 20 percent of the shares and the private equity company TPG Capital LP an 8 percent stake in the company, according to approval authorities.
Carnival, Royal Caribbean Cruises and Norwegian Cruises jointly hold more than 82 percent of the passenger capacity of American cruise ships, according to the original application documents for the listing of Prestige Cruises.
