Putin asks Kiev to start "statement talks" with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin, according to Russian media reports on Sunday, demanded that the Ukrainian government stop fighting against separatists in the east of the country and immediately start negotiations on the "statehood" of the abrogation region.
His spokesman, Dimitri Peskov, later made it clear that Putin did not mean that the territory of eastern Ukraine under the control of the separatists would become part of Russia, but that its status towards Ukraine had to be redefined in order to give the Russian-speaking region the power to represent its rights and interests.
However, Putin’s call for the Kiev government to negotiate at eye level with the pro-Russian insurgents is in line with the strategy he has apparently pursued since the beginning of the outbreaks five months ago: help for the separatists to seize territories and pressure on the Ukrainian government to allow the newly proclaimed region of Russia to maintain a de facto independence with the Novorossiya for the West.
In an interview with state-run TV channel One, Putin condemned the Ukrainian military campaign to recapture separatist-held areas in the eastern regions of Donetsk and Luhansk, which were seized in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian peninsula of Crimea on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently referred to the occupied territory as "Novorossia" or "Neurussland", a term reminiscent of the pre-revolutionary glorious period of the Russian Empire.
Putin pointed out that all those who, in the course of campaigns by Ukrainian politicians for the Oct. 26 elections and while government groups are attacking civilian communities in the separatist-held areas, are hoping for soon-to-be peace talks "caged in their illusions," Itar-Tass reported.
"We need to start in-depth discussions as soon as possible, not only on technical issues, but also on the political organization of society and the state status of South-Eastern Ukraine, in order to safeguard the interests of the people living there," he said.
Peskov said Putin’s reference to statehood must be seen in the context of the greater autonomy that has been discussed for months by the Kiev leadership to dispel fears in Russian-speaking areas that their cultural and linguistic rights are endangered.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the necessary autonomy to the eastern territories, Peskov said.
This is not about negotiations between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not about a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but about an internal conflict in Ukraine."
The Kremlin spokesman’s clarification of the correction of Putin’s “misinterpretation” of remarks underlined Russia’s leadership claim in dealing with the separatist rebellion in the East, in contrast to the direct annexation of Crimea, on which the majority of the 2 million inhabitants are ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have far greater difficulty in annexing the Donetsk and Luhansk regions of eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million residents are non-Russian and pre-conflict polls revealed a large majority for staying in Ukraine.
The autonomy addressed by Russian diplomats on international forums would give the regional governments in Ukraine authority to negotiate their own trade agreements and foreign relations, thus giving the Kremlin de facto control over an area that connects the Russian territory with Crimea.
The peninsula in the Black Sea annexed five months ago is the home port for most of the Russian Navy as well as an important trading port and historical coastal region.
The regions between the Rostov region in Russia and Crimea are also rich in mines, factories and foundries, which produce important components for the Russian military.
Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko proposed in his inaugural address on June 7 that the Ukrainian legislation should consider amendments to the constitution, after new elections, which would give the respective territories greater control over their finances and the status of the languages.
But his idea of autonomy seems to be in sharp contrast to those of the Kremlin and the separatist rebels, whose armament and incitement Moscow is accused of.
Putin’s last call for Kiev to negotiate with the separatist leaders at eye level followed a further incursion by rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks entered eastern Ukraine via the previously peaceful region along the Azov Sea.
Russia-backed separatists took control of Nowoasovsk, which according to fears of Ukrainian security officials is the first step in a campaign to take over the strategic coastal region to Crimea.
For this reason, massive civil and military preparations have taken place to fortify Mariupol, a steel industry port with 500,000 inhabitants, located between Nowoasovsk and the narrow access to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of the EU leadership in Brussels on Saturday, urging actions to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
"We are at a point where there is no going back," Poroshenko said.
Thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks are now on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit did not decide on any concrete actions, the leadership called for the draft of further sanctions against Russia, which should come into force in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukraine crisis.
Ukrainian soldiers had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovajsk after two Russian tank colonies and 1,000 soldiers invaded the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists, Colonel Andrij Lysenko, a spokesman for the Ukrainian National Security and Defense Council, said in a statement.
The first allegedly 63 Ukrainian soldiers captured by the Russian invasion of Ilovaysk were exchanged on Sunday for 10 Russian paratroopers captured on Ukrainian territory a week ago, Lysenko said on Sunday.
